{"componentChunkName":"component---src-pages-index-js","path":"/","result":{"data":{"hero":{"edges":[{"node":{"frontmatter":{"title":"Hello World! My name is","name":"Ryan A. Green","subtitle":"Pioneering climate solutions through mCDR research.","buttonText":"Contact Me"},"html":"<p>I'm a Ph.D. candidate at the University of California, Santa Cruz in the <a href=\"https://earth-system-biogeochemistry.net/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow noopener noreferrer\">Earth System Biogeochemistry Group</a>.</p>\n<p>I use biogeochemical modeling to research <a href=\"https://oceanvisions.org/ocean-based-carbon-dioxide-removal/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow noopener noreferrer\">marine carbon dioxide removal (mCDR)</a>, specifically through <a href=\"https://www.dosi-project.org/wp-content/uploads/Alkalinity-Enhancement-Policy-Brief.pdf\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow noopener noreferrer\">ocean alkalinity enhancement</a>.</p>"}}]},"about":{"edges":[{"node":{"frontmatter":{"title":"About Me","avatar":{"childImageSharp":{"fluid":{"tracedSVG":"data:image/jpeg;base64,","aspectRatio":0.8101851851851852,"src":"/static/58e4e5ad4b34a447e91cffe8da503dc3/ea4ab/me.jpg","srcSet":"/static/58e4e5ad4b34a447e91cffe8da503dc3/477ba/me.jpg 175w,\n/static/58e4e5ad4b34a447e91cffe8da503dc3/06776/me.jpg 350w,\n/static/58e4e5ad4b34a447e91cffe8da503dc3/ea4ab/me.jpg 700w,\n/static/58e4e5ad4b34a447e91cffe8da503dc3/213e3/me.jpg 859w","srcWebp":"/static/58e4e5ad4b34a447e91cffe8da503dc3/89afa/me.webp","srcSetWebp":"/static/58e4e5ad4b34a447e91cffe8da503dc3/9fca7/me.webp 175w,\n/static/58e4e5ad4b34a447e91cffe8da503dc3/37a4e/me.webp 350w,\n/static/58e4e5ad4b34a447e91cffe8da503dc3/89afa/me.webp 700w,\n/static/58e4e5ad4b34a447e91cffe8da503dc3/a568d/me.webp 859w","sizes":"(max-width: 700px) 100vw, 700px"}}},"skills":["Python","Carbonate Chemistry","C++","Isotope Geochemistry","Fortran","Paleoclimatology"]},"html":"<p>Welcome! I'm currently pursuing a Ph.D. with a focus on carbonate chemistry and biogeochemical modeling. Specifically, I'm fascinated by the potential of <a href=\"https://www.dosi-project.org/wp-content/uploads/Alkalinity-Enhancement-Policy-Brief.pdf\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow noopener noreferrer\">ocean alkalinity enhancement (OAE)</a> as a tool for <a href=\"https://oceanvisions.org/ocean-based-carbon-dioxide-removal/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow noopener noreferrer\">marine carbon dioxide removal (mCDR)</a>.</p>\n<p>Through my research, I've explored a range of projects related to OAE, from geologic analogs <strong>20,000 years ago</strong> to simulating future OAE off the west coast of the United States. I'm also interested in using <strong>carbon isotopes</strong> as a tool for verifying carbon uptake after mCDR.</p>\n<p>Outside of my research, I enjoy staying active and spending time outdoors. Some of my favorite activities include playing sports, cooking, and traveling with friends and family.</p>\n<p>Here is a list of the programming languages I use and the scientific topics that I am interested in!</p>"}}]},"jobs":{"edges":[{"node":{"frontmatter":{"title":"Ph.D. student","company":"UC Santa Cruz","range":"September 2019 - Present","url":"https://eps.ucsc.edu/"},"html":"<ul>\n<li>Advised by <a href=\"https://scholar.google.com/citations?user=3_YgMA0AAAAJ&#x26;hl=en\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow noopener noreferrer\">Dr. Mathis P. Hain</a> and co-advised by <a href=\"https://www.prafter.com/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow noopener noreferrer\">Dr. Patrick A. Rafter</a></li>\n<li>Using biogeochemical modeling, specifically with regional ocean models (ROMS) and box models, to study ocean alkalinity enhancement (OAE)</li>\n<li>Taking a dual approach to OAE research, examining analogs from the past and evaluating deployment in the future</li>\n<li>Funded by an <strong>NSF</strong> grant and an <strong>ARCS</strong> fellowship</li>\n<li>Also involved in mentoring undergraduate and high school students since 2021</li>\n</ul>"}},{"node":{"frontmatter":{"title":"Research Assistant","company":"University of New South Wales","range":"October 2018 - September 2019","url":"https://www.unsw.edu.au/research/ccrc"},"html":"<ul>\n<li>\n<p>Received a scholarship ($3800) to conduct research at the <a href=\"https://www.unsw.edu.au/research/ccrc\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow noopener noreferrer\">Climate Change Research Centre</a> within the University of New South Wales, while I was playing and coaching American football in Australia</p>\n</li>\n<li>\n<p>I worked with <a href=\"https://katrinmeissner.org/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow noopener noreferrer\">Prof. Katrin Meissner</a> and <a href=\"https://scholar.google.com/citations?user=gHh0AfoAAAAJ&#x26;hl=en\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow noopener noreferrer\">Prof. Laurie Menviel</a></p>\n</li>\n<li>\n<p>We analyzed seasonal sea-ice cover at the Last Glacial Maximum (LGM), to determine the most likely summer and winter sea-ice edge. Additionally, we constrained the mechanisms controlling sea ice in the PMIP3 and PMIP4 simulations.</p>\n</li>\n</ul>"}},{"node":{"frontmatter":{"title":"Undergraduate","company":"UC Davis","range":"September 2013 - March 2018","url":"https://www.ucdavis.edu/"},"html":"<ul>\n<li>Recieved a B.S. in Environmental Policy with a minor in Oceanography</li>\n<li>Performed research in the <a href=\"http://www.des.ucdavis.edu/faculty/baskett/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow noopener noreferrer\">Baskett Lab</a> and the <a href=\"https://stachlab.wordpress.com/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow noopener noreferrer\">Stachowicz Lab</a></li>\n<li>Was a student-athlete as a member of the Division-1 intercollegiate football program</li>\n</ul>"}}]},"featured":{"edges":[{"node":{"frontmatter":{"title":"Geologic Analogs to OAE","cover":{"childImageSharp":{"fluid":{"tracedSVG":"data:image/jpeg;base64,","aspectRatio":1.5086206896551724,"src":"/static/f5d48644fae89df3c5befc833923ad87/61b9e/ocean_hotspots_east_pacific.jpg","srcSet":"/static/f5d48644fae89df3c5befc833923ad87/477ba/ocean_hotspots_east_pacific.jpg 175w,\n/static/f5d48644fae89df3c5befc833923ad87/06776/ocean_hotspots_east_pacific.jpg 350w,\n/static/f5d48644fae89df3c5befc833923ad87/61b9e/ocean_hotspots_east_pacific.jpg 611w","srcWebp":"/static/f5d48644fae89df3c5befc833923ad87/12df1/ocean_hotspots_east_pacific.webp","srcSetWebp":"/static/f5d48644fae89df3c5befc833923ad87/9fca7/ocean_hotspots_east_pacific.webp 175w,\n/static/f5d48644fae89df3c5befc833923ad87/37a4e/ocean_hotspots_east_pacific.webp 350w,\n/static/f5d48644fae89df3c5befc833923ad87/12df1/ocean_hotspots_east_pacific.webp 611w","sizes":"(max-width: 611px) 100vw, 611px"}}},"tech":["OAE","Deglaciation","Carbon Cycle Modeling"],"github":null,"external":null},"html":"<p>We investivgated carbon isotope anomalies in the Pacific over the last 20,000 years,  suggesting alkalinity-neutralized carbon was released from a geologic source (i.e., analog to OAE). We found that <strong>~2400</strong> gigatons of neutralized carbon could have been added (that is <strong>~6X</strong> what humans have emitted since the industrial revolution!). We simulated this <u>without</u> causing a significant increase in atmospheric CO<sub>2</sub> or ocean acidification. This demonstrates <strong>two things:</strong> <strong>1.</strong> the ocean's immense capacity to remove carbon with alkalinity and <strong>2.</strong> the limited impacts it would have on the marine system, globaly and regionally. Our first manuscript outlining this work is under review at <strong><em>Geophysical Research Letters</em></strong>, and we have one more publication in preparation.</p>\n<!-- Photo from MBARI. -->\n<!-- - To do this, we built a regional model for the Gulf of California region where the carbon isotope anomalies are observed, and coupled the model to a global carbon cycle model. We then developed numerical inversion methods to assimilate reconstructed carbon cycle changes and quantify how much alkalinity-neutralized carbon was plausible. -->"}},{"node":{"frontmatter":{"title":"Using Carbon Isotopes for MRV","cover":{"childImageSharp":{"fluid":{"tracedSVG":"data:image/jpeg;base64,","aspectRatio":1.1986301369863013,"src":"/static/979a601e44f752f7f4f83f94cd61d631/ea4ab/global_trends_D13c.jpg","srcSet":"/static/979a601e44f752f7f4f83f94cd61d631/477ba/global_trends_D13c.jpg 175w,\n/static/979a601e44f752f7f4f83f94cd61d631/06776/global_trends_D13c.jpg 350w,\n/static/979a601e44f752f7f4f83f94cd61d631/ea4ab/global_trends_D13c.jpg 700w","srcWebp":"/static/979a601e44f752f7f4f83f94cd61d631/89afa/global_trends_D13c.webp","srcSetWebp":"/static/979a601e44f752f7f4f83f94cd61d631/9fca7/global_trends_D13c.webp 175w,\n/static/979a601e44f752f7f4f83f94cd61d631/37a4e/global_trends_D13c.webp 350w,\n/static/979a601e44f752f7f4f83f94cd61d631/89afa/global_trends_D13c.webp 700w","sizes":"(max-width: 700px) 100vw, 700px"}}},"tech":["Carbon Isotopes","mCDR MRV"],"github":null,"external":null},"html":"<p>Carbon isotopes (i.e., δ<sup>13</sup>C) can be used to verify carbon dioxide removal by providing a unique fingerprint from its atmospheric source (i.e., <a href=\"https://gml.noaa.gov/ccgg/isotopes/c13tellsus.html\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow noopener noreferrer\">The Suess Effect</a>, see NOAA figure on right). We built a carbon isotope-enabled mixed-layer box model and simulated simplified ocean alkalinity enhancement experiments, comparing the δ<sup>13</sup>C signal to other carbonate parameters. Our preliminary results suggest that the δ<sup>13</sup>C signal after mCDR will last longer than other carbonate parameters, therefore making it easier to detect and verify the carbon uptake (aka monitoring, reporting, and verification – MRV) after OAE.</p>"}},{"node":{"frontmatter":{"title":"Simulating OAE with ROMS","cover":{"childImageSharp":{"fluid":{"tracedSVG":"data:image/png;base64,","aspectRatio":0.8101851851851852,"src":"/static/146e1750eca832655ee281644b941f5b/60290/CAcurrent.png","srcSet":"/static/146e1750eca832655ee281644b941f5b/847ef/CAcurrent.png 175w,\n/static/146e1750eca832655ee281644b941f5b/91cba/CAcurrent.png 350w,\n/static/146e1750eca832655ee281644b941f5b/60290/CAcurrent.png 700w,\n/static/146e1750eca832655ee281644b941f5b/a04a8/CAcurrent.png 864w","srcWebp":"/static/146e1750eca832655ee281644b941f5b/89afa/CAcurrent.webp","srcSetWebp":"/static/146e1750eca832655ee281644b941f5b/9fca7/CAcurrent.webp 175w,\n/static/146e1750eca832655ee281644b941f5b/37a4e/CAcurrent.webp 350w,\n/static/146e1750eca832655ee281644b941f5b/89afa/CAcurrent.webp 700w,\n/static/146e1750eca832655ee281644b941f5b/65e54/CAcurrent.webp 864w","sizes":"(max-width: 700px) 100vw, 700px"}}},"tech":["California Current","ROMS","OAE"],"github":null,"external":null},"html":"<p>This project will use the Regional Ocean Modeling System (ROMS) configured for the California Current System (<a href=\"https://agupubs.onlinelibrary.wiley.com/doi/full/10.1002/2013GB004683\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow noopener noreferrer\">CCS-ROMS</a>) coupled to a biogeochemical model (NEMUCSC) to simulate various OAE experiments with different locations and dispersal techniques. The coast of California has been designated as an <a href=\"https://bg.copernicus.org/articles/20/27/2023/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow noopener noreferrer\">ideal location</a> for OAE. Our simulations will be conducted at a spatial resolution of 3 km, and thus provide valuable insights into the localized impacts, far-field detectability of added carbon storage, and overall efficiency of different OAE scenarios. Figure from <a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/California_Current\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow noopener noreferrer\">Wikipedia</a>.</p>"}}]},"projects":{"edges":[{"node":{"frontmatter":{"title":"Neutralized Carbon Added During the Last Deglaciation","tech":["Neutralized Carbon","Deglaciation","∆14C anomalies"],"github":"","external":"https://www.authorea.com/doi/full/10.22541/essoar.168286659.92261243"},"html":"<p>Currently under review at <em>Geophysical Research Letters</em>, but the preprint is available at <a href=\"https://www.authorea.com/doi/full/10.22541/essoar.168286659.92261243\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow noopener noreferrer\">Authorea</a>.</p>"}},{"node":{"frontmatter":{"title":"Evaluating Seasonal Sea-ice Cover at the LGM","tech":["LGM","Sea ice","GCMs","PMIP"],"github":null,"external":"https://cp.copernicus.org/articles/18/845/2022/"},"html":"<p>Published in <a href=\"https://cp.copernicus.org/articles/18/845/2022/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow noopener noreferrer\"><em>Climate of the Past</em></a>.</p>"}}]},"contact":{"edges":[{"node":{"frontmatter":{"title":"Get In Touch","buttonText":"Say Hello"},"html":"<p>I will be finishing my Ph.D. next summer and looking for work in the mCDR field. If you're interested in learning more about my research or connecting with me, please reach out!</p>"}}]}},"pageContext":{}},"staticQueryHashes":["3115057458"]}